    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i think it might be nitrogen. is there a specific way to check the ph levels to make sure the nutrients are actually getting through? also how do i tell if something else is eating the nutrients before the plant can get them?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Checking the pH level of your soil can help ensure your plants are able to absorb the nutrients effectively. Use a soil pH test kit, which is easily available at garden centers, to measure the pH. The ideal pH range for tomato plants is between 6.0 and 6.8. If the pH is outside this range, you can adjust it by using soil amendments.\n\nAs for other issues, pests like nematodes, slugs, and other insects could be consuming your plant's roots and, in doing so, preventing your plants from accessing nutrients. Inspect the base and underside of your leaves and yellowed plants for tunnel marks, root damage, or insect damage. Control pests with organic or chemical treatments depending on the type and severity. It's also crucial that your plants are free of disease, so look for signs like spots or wilting and isolate any affected plants to prevent spread. Regular monitoring will help you stay ahead of any nutrient stealing issues.",
