    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "makes sense. the \"nutrient stealing\" thing is what worries me though. i haven't seen any bugs or slugs around, so i'm wondering if something else is just... draining it. like is there any other reason the nutrients might just disappear from the soil?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If pests are not the cause, then other factors could lead to reduced nutrient availability for your plants. Soil conditions like compaction, poor drainage, or erosion could potentially cause nutrients to leach away before the plants can access them. Additionally, over-fertilizing or improper fertilization practices might result in nutrient lockout, where plants can't absorb certain nutrients effectively. \n\nAnother consideration is that the root system might be damaged or diseased, which can limit the plant's ability to take up nutrients. Make sure the soil structure and drainage are optimal, and be careful with the fertilizer application—follow the recommended guidelines for the type of soil and the growth stage of your tomato plants to avoid excessive buildup. Regularly rotating your crops and practicing good soil hygiene can also help prevent many of these issues.\n\nIf you're still concerned about root damage from \"nutrient stealing,\" you might want to consider root inspection using a small, clean hole at the base of the plant to look for any root problems. If you find damaged roots, you can trim them off to encourage healthy new growth while taking care to clean the plant's base to prevent disease. Remember, though, that not all visible \"stealing\" comes from pests or animals – plants also naturally draw nutrients",
      "source": "target",
